==Latin==
===Etymology=== From earlier {{term||*egni, *igni|lang=la}}, dissimilated from {{term||*engni, *ingni|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|la}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*h₁n̥gʷnis||fire}}. Cognate with Sanskrit {{term|अग्नि|tr=agní|sc=Deva|lang=sa}}, Hittite {{term|sc=Xsux|𒀀𒀝𒉌𒅖|tr=akniš|lang=hit}} (an Indo-Iranian borrowing), Old Church Slavonic {{term|sc=Cyrl|огнь|tr=ognĭ|lang=cu}} and Old Prussian {{term|ugnis|lang=prg}}.
===Pronunciation=== * {{a|ecclesiastical}} {{IPA|/ˈi.ɲis/|lang=la}} * {{audio|La-ecc-ignis.ogg|audio (ecclesiastical)}} * {{a|classical}} {{IPA|/ˈiŋ.nis/|lang=la}} * {{audio|La-cls-ignis.ogg|audio (classical)}}
===Noun=== {{la-noun|ignis|ignis|ignis|m|third}} # [[fire]] #: ''ferro '''igni'''que.'' #:: With iron and '''[with] fire'''. #* '''29–19 {{B.C.E.}}''', [[w:Virgil|Virgil]], ''[[w:Aeneid|Aeneid]]'', 8.420 #*: striduntque cauernis / stricturae Chalybum et fornacibus '''ignis''' anhelat #*:: ''Chalybian ores hiss in the caverns, and from the furnace mouths puff the hot-panting '''fires'''''
====Inflection==== {{la-decl-3rd-I-ignis|ignis|ign}}
====Derived terms==== * {{l|la|ignēscō|gloss=to kindle, burn}} * {{l|la|igniō|gloss=to ignite}} * {{l|la|igneus|gloss=fiery}} * {{l|la|ignifer|gloss=bearing fire}}
